  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that modern developer laptops have become high-value targets for attackers due to their role as \"credential warehouses,\" storing sensitive data like API keys, SSH keys, and cloud CLI configurations. The core thesis is that mundane user actions—opening files, clicking links, or installing tools—can lead to catastrophic breaches by exploiting these stored credentials. Key technologies discussed include infostealers like Microsoft’s Lumma Stealer and real-world campaigns such as Mandiant’s UNC5537, which highlight how stolen credentials (often from backups or local files) enable infrastructure access. The tone is analytical and cautionary, framing the laptop as a \"junk room\" of unsecured trust artifacts. Recurring metaphors include the \"desk drawer\" of forgotten backups and the \"city of half-trusted doors\" attackers exploit. The intended audience is developers and security professionals tasked with securing local environments against low",
